<tr>
<td>
<div class="noprint plainlinksneverexpand navbar" style="background:none; padding:0; font-weight:normal;; font-size:xx-small;">This box: <a href="/wiki/Template:Hindu_philosophy" title="Template:Hindu philosophy"><span title="View this template" style="">view</span></a>&#160;<span style="font-size:80%;">•</span>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Template_talk:Hindu_philosophy" title="Template talk:Hindu philosophy"><span title="Discussion about this template" style="">talk</span></a>&#160;<span style="font-size:80%;">•</span>&#160;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Hindu_philosophy&amp;action=edit" class="external text" title="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Hindu_philosophy&amp;action=edit" rel="nofollow"><span title="Edit this template" style=";">edit</span></a></div>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><b>Advaita</b> (literally, <i><a href="/wiki/Non-dual" title="Non-dual" class="mw-redirect">non-duality</a></i>) is more often than not interpreted as <a href="/wiki/Monism" title="Monism">monism</a>/<a href="/wiki/Monistic" title="Monistic" class="mw-redirect">monistic</a> system of thought. Otherwise called <b>Advaita Vedanta</b> (<a href="/wiki/IAST" title="IAST" class="mw-redirect">IAST</a> <i><span lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="sa-Latn">Advaita Vedānta</span></i>; <a href="/wiki/Sanskrit" title="Sanskrit">Sanskrit</a> <span class="Unicode">अद्वैत वेदान्त</span>; <small>IPA</small>:&#160;<span title="Pronunciation in IPA" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:IPA" title="Wikipedia:IPA">[əd̪vait̪ə veːd̪ɑːnt̪ə]</a></span>), it is a school of <a href="/wiki/Ved%C4%81nta" title="Vedānta" class="mw-redirect">Vedānta</a> (literally, <i>end or the goal of the <a href="/wiki/Vedas" title="Vedas">Vedas</a></i>, <a href="/wiki/Sanskrit" title="Sanskrit">Sanskrit</a>) school of <a href="/wiki/Hindu_philosophy" title="Hindu philosophy">Hindu philosophy</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> Other major schools of <a href="/wiki/Ved%C4%81nta" title="Vedānta" class="mw-redirect">Vedānta</a> are <i><a href="/wiki/Dvaita" title="Dvaita">Dvaita</a></i> and <i><span lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="sa-Latn"><a href="/wiki/Vishishtadvaita" title="Vishishtadvaita">Viśishṭādvaita</a></span></i>. <i>Advaita</i> ("not two") refers to the identity of the Self (<a href="/wiki/Atman_(Hinduism)" title="Atman (Hinduism)" class="mw-redirect">Atman</a>) with <a href="/wiki/Brahman" title="Brahman">Brahman</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> <i>Advaita</i> is not a theistic philosophy, and does not advocate worship of a singular all powerful supreme being/<a href="/wiki/Ishwara" title="Ishwara" class="mw-redirect">Ishwara</a>/<a href="/wiki/God" title="God">God</a>. It is about realising the self, i.e. the <i><a href="/wiki/Atman" title="Atman">Atman</a></i>, as the <i><a href="/wiki/Brahman" title="Brahman">Brahman</a></i> itself which is apparently manifested eternally and simultaneously into animate or inanimate. This realization is limited and/or inhibited by lack of knowledge and discrimination, i.e. <i><a href="/wiki/Jnana" title="Jnana">Jnana</a></i>, and this verily is the foundation of non-duality (Advaita). The concept of <i><a href="/wiki/Brahman" title="Brahman">Brahman</a></i> is understood by the use of the phrase <i><a href="/wiki/Neti_neti" title="Neti neti">neti neti</a></i> (ná iti ná iti - not this, not this or not so not so) in the <i><a href="/wiki/Upanishad" title="Upanishad" class="mw-redirect">Upanishads</a></i>. The principal <a href="/wiki/Upanishad" title="Upanishad" class="mw-redirect">Upanishads</a>, <i><a href="/wiki/Brahma_Sutras" title="Brahma Sutras">Brahma Sutras</a></i> as well as <i><a href="/wiki/Badarayana" title="Badarayana" class="mw-redirect">Badarayana</a></i>, <a href="/wiki/Adi_Shankara" title="Adi Shankara">Adi Shankara</a> and <a href="/wiki/Ashtavakra" title="Ashtavakra">Ashtavakra</a> have expounded this philosophy.</p>
<p>The key source texts for all schools of <span lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="sa-Latn">Vedānta</span> are the <a href="/wiki/Prasthanatrayi" title="Prasthanatrayi">Prasthanatrayi</a>—the canonical texts consisting of the <a href="/wiki/Upanishad" title="Upanishad" class="mw-redirect">Upanishads</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Brahma_Sutras" title="Brahma Sutras">Brahma Sutras</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Bhagavad_Gita" title="Bhagavad Gita">Bhagavad Gita</a>. The first person to explicitly consolidate the principles of Advaita Vedanta was <a href="/wiki/Adi_Shankara" title="Adi Shankara">Adi Shankara</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> while the first known historical proponent was <a href="/wiki/Gaudapada" title="Gaudapada">Gaudapada</a>, the guru of Shankara's guru <a href="/wiki/Govinda_Bhagavatpada" title="Govinda Bhagavatpada">Govinda Bhagavatpada</a>.</p>
